explanation:
- OS_CHECK_POINTER: This macro is invoked on the timer_name parameter. Its definition may access or log the pointer (or call other routines that do), so you must inspect it to ensure it does not call any <string.h> functions (or use %s logging) that could read beyond the supplied buffer.
- OS_ObjectIdFindByName: This is the direct callee that receives timer_name. Its implementation must be inspected to see if it calls any <string.h> routines (e.g. strcmp/strcpy/strncpy/strlen/memcpy) and whether those calls can read or write beyond the bounds of timer_name or other buffers.
- OS_ObjectIdGetByName: OS_ObjectIdFindByName calls this function. It likely performs the actual name comparisons or copies; therefore its use of standard string functions (and any buffer-size assumptions) must be examined.
- OS_ObjectIdRelease: Although less likely to touch the input string, it is a callee of ObjectIdFindByName and may participate in resource handling that involves name buffers. Include it to ensure no indirect string operations occur there.
- OS_printf: Logging routines (often used by parameter-check macros or error paths) can be passed strings or use %s and thus may attempt to read the provided timer_name. Inspect OS_printf to ensure it does not assume null-terminated input or otherwise read past the buffer.

These symbols together cover all code paths in the target function that receive or could access the timer_name argument; examining their implementations is necessary to determine whether any standard <string.h> function is invoked in a way that could access memory beyond the timer_name (or destination) bounds, thereby violating the MISRA rule.
